Btw. To go back to silk Road. How did tor function? (Or does it still function) why are those pages not indexed thru other search engines but visible thru tor?

Tor still functions, yes.
The short version: regular internet traffic goes directly from your device to the destination server, which means anyone watching the connection — your ISP, government, whoever — can see where you're going. 
Tor routes your traffic through a series of volunteer-run relay nodes, each one only knowing the previous and next hop, never the full path. By the time you reach the destination, the origin is obscured. 
It's layered encryption — hence "onion" routing, Tor stands for The Onion Router.
The dark web pages you saw — .onion addresses — aren't indexed by Google or regular search engines for a structural reason: they're not on the regular internet at all. 
They're hosted on servers that are themselves only reachable through the Tor network. There's no IP address to find, no domain registered with a registrar, nothing for a regular crawler to discover. 
You can only reach them if you're inside the network.
So it's not that Google refuses to index them. It's that Google's crawlers can't even see them — they exist in a separate address space that's only accessible through Tor's routing system.
The exit node is the weak point — the last relay that actually contacts the destination can potentially be monitored, which is why Silk Road and similar markets used .onion addresses instead of regular websites. 
Traffic never had to leave the Tor network at all.
Still used today for legitimate privacy purposes — journalists, activists in authoritarian countries, whistleblowers. And yes, still the same dark ecosystem you visited for fifteen minutes in the silk road days.

